4. Methods
Specifically, the study follows these steps (overarching goals in parenthesis):



Theory \(\rightarrow\) Estimand(s) \(\rightarrow\) Design (Tutorial and Model validation)
Considering three steps: (1) define the CJ structure and explicitly state its assumptions from relevant literature, (2) specify the estimand(s) of interest and provide formal definitions for each target parameter, and (3) simulate a synthetic conceptual population that reflects the defined structure and assumptions;
Design \(\rightarrow\) Sample (Tutorial and Model validation)
Generate two synthetic samples and comparison datasets from the conceptual population in step \(3\);
{Theory, Design, Estimand(s)} \(\rightarrow\) Estimator (Tutorial and Model validation)
Specify models for analyzing the first synthetic comparison dataset using both the classical BTL analysis and the Information-Theoretical model for CJ;
Estimator \(\rightarrow\) Prior predictive (Tutorial)
Perform prior predictive checks;

4. Methods



{Estimator, Sample} \(\rightarrow\) Estimate(s) (Tutorial and Model validation)
Apply both the classical BTL model and the Information-Theoretical model for CJ to the first synthetic comparison dataset;
Estimate(s) \(\rightarrow\) {Diagnostic, Post predictive} (Tutorial)
Assess the quality of the models and estimate(s) in terms of convergence, parameter recovery, in-sample fit, out-of-sample fit, and in-sample predictive accuracy;
{Diagnostic, Post predictive} \(\rightarrow\) Estimator (Tutorial)
Incrementally refine the model specified in step 5, repeating steps 5–9 until a sufficiently trustworthy model is obtained according to the criteria outlined in step 8;
Estimator \(\rightarrow\) Estimate(s) \(\rightarrow\) Effects \(\leftarrow\) Estimand(s) (Model validation)
Generate the estimate(s) of interest for CJ the first synthetic comparison dataset using both the classical BTL analysis and the Information-Theoretical model, and interpret the results;
Estimator \(\rightarrow\) Estimate(s) \(\rightarrow\) Predictions \(\leftarrow\) Estimand(s) (Model validation)
Generate predictions for the second synthetic comparison dataset using both the classical BTL analysis and the Information-Theoretical model for CJ, and compare their out-of-sample predictive accuracy.

4.2 From Design to Sample: Step 2
Differing only by replication seed, the study generates two synthetic samples and comparison datasets from the conceptual population.

More specifically, for the sampling and comparison mechanisms illustrated in Figure 4 (\(S\) and \(C\), respectively) the study conducts sample size calculations (see next slides) and adopts the following design:


A sample of \(54\) individuals, divided into three groups: \(40\) normal-hearing (NH, \(g=1\)), \(7\) hearing-impaired with hearing aids (HI-HA, \(g=2\)), and \(7\) hearing-impaired with cochlear implants (HI-CI, \(g=3\));
A sample of \(10\) stimuli per individual;
A sample of \(60\) judges, divided into three groups: \(10\) audiologist (AU, \(g=1\)), \(10\) primary teachers (PT, \(g=2\)), and \(40\) inexperienced listeners (IL, \(g=3\));
Judges conduct only one-comparison of the same stimulus pair (i.e., NOT repeated measures design [25])
Each stimulus is compared a total of \(20\) times again another stimulus, across all judges.

